AFRICAN SWINE FEVER - UKRAINE (03): (LUHANSK) DOMESTIC PIG, CONFIRMED, OIE
**************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 3 Feb 2014
Source: ThePigSite [edited]
http://www.thepigsite.com/swinenews/35605/african-swine-fever-outbreak-in-ukraine


The Ukrainian veterinary authorities have reported an outbreak of African swine fever [ASF] at a pig farm in [Luhansk]. The World Organisation for Animal Health (OIE) received an immediate notification on Fri 31 Jan 2014. The outbreak reportedly first occurred on 6 Jan 2014.

Direct immunofluorescence (DIF) and polymerase chain reaction (PCR) tests were carried out at the Luhansk Regional State Laboratory of Veterinary Medicine on 31 Jan 2014. Both tests resulted positive. According to the report, a total of 26 pigs were found susceptible, out of which 5 cases as well as deaths were reported. No animals were destroyed and/or slaughtered.

Control of wildlife reservoirs, quarantine, movement control inside the country, screening, and zoning are some of the control measures that have been applied to control the situation. The source of the outbreak has not yet been determined.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The current outbreak affecting domestic pigs, the suspicion of which is included in ProMED-mail posting African swine fever - Ukraine (02): (LH) spread susp, RFI 20140116.2177657, is situated in the Luhansk oblast, Eastern Ukraine, bordering Russia -- similar to the earlier outbreak in Ukraine, involving a wild boar which was detected on 6 Jan 2014. The 1st ASF outbreak in Ukraine was diagnosed in South Ukraine in July 2012 and declared resolved in December 2012.

The outbreak described above has been reported on 31 Jan 2014 to the OIE. For an OIE summary of the 2 recent outbreaks, with a map, please see http://tinyurl.com/o7eacav. - Mod.AS

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/9OP2.]
